{
  "title": "Per du mit dem Minister",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ec5eebc5942a32f5",
      "text": "\nHow Robert Habeck rhetorically immunizes himself against criticism"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ba8d29be80d7627",
      "text": "Robert Habeck is widely celebrated for his communication style. He also repeatedly addresses negative aspects of his own policies. A real politician could hardly be more clever in immunizing himself against criticism.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d0d02602501c2bac",
      "text": "Commentary by [[Felix Klopotek]] (2022-04-14) [https://jungle.world/artikel/2022/15/du-mit-dem-minister post] (de)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dd6e325a669bc1c8",
      "text": "A popular prejudice about the Greens is that they carry lofty ideals in front of them and make big promises, but when given the opportunity, fail to fulfill them. The Greens are seen as the great hypocrites and bigots of politics. Leftists state this bitterly, conservatives with satisfaction, perhaps even with a hint of recognition. But this prejudice has never really hurt the Greens. On the contrary, one might almost say. The appearance of Robert Habeck as Federal Minister for the Economy and Climate Protection seems to confirm this."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ab14c6129665609",
      "text": "Habeck is considered the rhetor of the German government. Not because he speaks in a polished and pointed manner, but because he searches and gropes, avoids diplomatic phrases, sometimes even loops around, but always addresses his audience directly. That makes an impression - an adult speaking to adults. The public is full of praise: Habeck's \"ambivalence and unsparing openness in communication\" is \"impressive and completely new in this form,\" writes an editor of the Tagesspiegel on Twitter. Habeck addresses dilemmas openly, it is said again and again, he exposes doubts and self-doubts and talks bluntly about the deficits of his policies, which are the deficits of this society - that is his backdoor, because he can't do anything for them."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0b40d9879a84f0bc",
      "text": "His appearance on \"Markus Lanz\" in the March 31 broadcast brought him much recognition in the social media. Habeck had previously been in Qatar to negotiate a new \"energy partnership\" - and now defended himself against criticism by denouncing hypocritical moralism himself. \"We are blazing a trail of devastation through the earth with our daily lives,\" he raged. He lamented the self-deception of a society whose gasoline is derived from Saudi oil and for whose mince pies creatures suffer miserably on mass farms - and which, at the same time, gets upset when the minister sets up deals with Qatar. This is what it was all about: Habeck was accused of merely replacing one devil, Vladimir Putin, with another, namely a ruling clique that is a party to one of the most victimized wars of this time - the civil war in Yemen - and exploits countless migrant workers under the worst conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7bec9a8d241e1b9d",
      "text": "Of course, Habeck also remains a moralist, pointing his finger at society, at \"us\". Look here, he says, we are all bigoted, we are all comfortable and have never liked to look, neither in the Donbass nor in our disgusting pigsties. It's not my fault if the Greens can't realize their ideals, it's the fault of a society that lets itself get along far too well. Habeck makes the gap between aspiration and reality productive: It is an incentive for him to really get down to business - and, of course, it is the legitimation to get the citizens in the mood for hard times. He accepts the reproach of not living up to his own moral standards and still uses it to justify himself. No matter how mumbled he sounds when he speaks, rhetorically it is a tour de force."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5a36c638981886bf",
      "text": "While still in Qatar three weeks ago, Habeck addressed his domestic audience directly in a clip published on his ministry's YouTube channel, explaining the supply contracts he had negotiated. In the video, he ducks[?] the audience and lets them in on how \"somehow totally weird\" this trip felt. He also addresses the fatal labor situation in Qatar, but shows appreciation that the Qatari government promises to adopt better labor laws. The fact that he is thus indirectly saying that the living conditions of most of the three million migrant workers in Qatar are still catastrophic - forget it; the main thing is that he has \"addressed\" the grievances. That is the clever thing about Habeck's rhetoric: It uses the [[contradiction]]s on which it is based in a variety of ways - sometimes as a reproach to the population; sometimes as a demand on himself to always do a little better, in his words: to continue working on the structures."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "619dc2faddbe0011",
      "text": "This shows that a criticism of the Greens that aims at exposure and demonstration falls short. The Greens have lived with this [[contradiction]] for a long time and can now even claim it as their real strength. It doesn't change anything about the circumstances, the structures, as Habeck would say. But it is all the easier for them to sell the hardships that they and their coalition partners are imposing on the population as necessary, as a painful but correct step."
    }
