      "type": "edit",
      "id": "5a36c638981886bf",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5a36c638981886bf",
        "text": "While still in Qatar three weeks ago, Habeck addressed his domestic audience directly in a clip published on his ministry's YouTube channel, explaining the supply contracts he had negotiated. In the video, he ducks the audience and lets them in on how \"somehow totally weird\" this trip felt. He also addresses the fatal labor situation in Qatar, but shows appreciation that the Qatari government promises to adopt better labor laws. The fact that he is thus indirectly saying that the living conditions of most of the three million migrant workers in Qatar are still catastrophic - forget it; the main thing is that he has \"addressed\" the grievances. That is the clever thing about Habeck's rhetoric: It uses the contradictions on which it is based in a variety of ways - sometimes as a reproach to the population; sometimes as a demand on himself to always do a little better, in his words: to continue working on the structures."
